{"questionId":"2526107","questionHtml":"<p>The side lengths, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo> </mo><mi>cm</mi></math>, of an equilateral triangle are increasing at a rate of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mo> </mo><mi>cm</mi><mo> </mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>.</p>\n<p>Find the rate at which the area of the triangle, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>A</mi><mo> </mo><msup><mi>cm</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math>, is increasing when the side lengths are <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mo> </mo><mi>cm</mi></math>.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>A</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo> </mo><mi>sin</mi><mfrac><mi>π</mi><mn>3</mn></mfrac></math> OR <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>A</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mn>60</mn><mo> </mo><mo>°</mo></math>&nbsp; OR&nbsp; triangle height <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>h</mi><mo>=</mo><msqrt><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><msup><mfenced><mfrac><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup></msqrt><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mfenced><mfrac><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mfenced></math>&nbsp; OR&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>A</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mi>x</mi><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfenced><mfenced><mrow><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mn>4</mn></mfrac><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Award <em><strong>A1</strong></em> for <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>sin</mi><mfrac><mi>π</mi><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math>. This may be seen at a later stage.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:left;\">&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:left;\">attempt to use chain rule or implicit differentiation&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:left;\">&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:left;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi>A</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi>A</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>×</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi>x</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:left;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi>A</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mo>×</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>x</mi><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi>x</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac></math> OR <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi>A</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>×</mo><mi>sin</mi><mfrac><mi>π</mi><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mo>×</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>x</mi><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi>x</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:left;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt></mrow><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mo>×</mo><mn>5</mn><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mo>×</mo><mn>4</mn></math></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:left;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mtext>d</mtext><mi>A</mi></mrow><mrow><mtext>d</mtext><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>30</mn><mo> </mo><mo>(</mo><msup><mi>cm</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo> </mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mo>)</mo></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:left;\">&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:left;\"><strong>Note:&nbsp;</strong>Award a maximum of&nbsp;<em><strong>(A1)A1(M1)(A0)A1</strong></em>&nbsp;for a correct answer with incorrect derivative notation seen throughout.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:left;\">&nbsp;<br><em><strong>[5 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"2526107","referenceCode":"23M.1.AHL.TZ1.6","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"The side lengths, x cm, of an equilateral triangle are increasing at a rate of 4 cm s-1. Find the rate at which the area of the triangle, A cm2, is increasing when the side lengths","paper":"1","level":"HL","questionNumber":"6","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 5]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","Topic 5 —Calculus","Topic 5 —Calculus","SL 5.3—Differentiating polynomials, n E Z","Topic 5 —Calculus","AHL 5.14—Implicit functions, related rates, optimisation","Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","SL 3.2—2d and 3d trig, sine rule, cosine rule, area"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}